en.explanation:
x + y + z = 5<br><br>
x + 2y + 2z = 6<br><br>
x + 3y + $$\lambda $$z = $$\mu $$ have infinite solution<br><br>
$$\Delta $$ = 0, $$\Delta $$x = $$\Delta $$y = $$\Delta $$z = 0<br><br>
$$\Delta  = \left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 1 &amp; 1  \cr 
   1 &amp; 2 &amp; 2  \cr 
   1 &amp; 3 &amp; \lambda   \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$<br><br>
$$ \Rightarrow 1(2\lambda  - 6) - 1(\lambda  - 2) + 1(3 - 2) = 0$$<br><br>
$$ \Rightarrow 2\lambda  - 6 - \lambda  + 2 + 1 = 0$$<br><br>
$$ \Rightarrow \lambda  = 3$$<br><br>
Now, $$\Delta x = \left| {\matrix{
   5 &amp; 1 &amp; 1  \cr 
   6 &amp; 2 &amp; 2  \cr 
   \mu  &amp; 3 &amp; 3  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$,<br><br> $$\Delta $$y = $$\left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 5 &amp; 1  \cr 
   1 &amp; 6 &amp; 2  \cr 
   1 &amp; \mu  &amp; 3  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$<br><br>
$$ \Rightarrow \left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 5 &amp; 1  \cr 
   0 &amp; 1 &amp; 1  \cr 
   0 &amp; {\mu  - 5} &amp; 2  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$<br><br>
$$ \Rightarrow \mu  = 7$$<br><br>
$$\Delta z = \left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 1 &amp; 5  \cr 
   1 &amp; 2 &amp; 6  \cr 
   1 &amp; 3 &amp; \mu   \cr 

 } } \right| = \left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 1 &amp; 5  \cr 
   0 &amp; { - 1} &amp; { - 1}  \cr 
   0 &amp; 2 &amp; {\mu  - 5}  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>
$$ \Rightarrow 1(5 - \mu  + 2) = 0$$<br><br>
$$ \Rightarrow \mu  = 7$$<br><br>
So, $$\lambda  + \mu  = 10$$
